atsakis/events{/privacy}", "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/nikomatsakis/received_events", "type": "User", "site_admin": false}, "open_issues": 0, "closed_issues": 8, "state": "closed", "created_at": "2018-01-19T16:48:35Z", "updated_at": "2018-07-24T14:21:33Z", "due_on": null, "closed_at": "2018-03-14T20:41:12Z"}, "comments": 2, "created_at": "2018-02-22T01:46:33Z", "updated_at": "2018-04-03T15:27:41Z", "closed_at": "2018-04-03T15:27:40Z", "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR", "active_lock_reason": null, "body": "As uncovered in https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/47689, two-phase borrows as implemented can lead to \"extra\" and confusing error messages. The problem is that each time we have a \"gen \" of the activation, we do the activation check -- but if there are two activations in a row, each of them can emit an error, when we only want an error from the first.\r\n\r\nThe `HEAD~1` commit in [branch `issue-48418` on my repository](https://github.com/nikomatsakis/rust/tree/issue-48418) fixes the problem, but probably not in a sound way, as [discussed in this commit (and its successor)](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/47689#issuecomment-367354718). \r\n\r\nThe proper fix either involves adding a dominator check (suppress activation of bit B at A2 if it is dominated by another activation of bit B at A1), or else a \"must activate\" sort of analysis.\r\n\r\ncc @pnkfelix ", "closed_by": {"login": "nikomatsakis", "id": 155238, "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjE1NTIzOA==", "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/155238?v=4", "gravatar_id": "", "url": "https://api.github.com/users/nikomatsakis", "html_url": "https://github.com/nikomatsakis", "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/nikomatsakis/followers", "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/nikomatsakis/following{/other_user}", "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/nikomatsakis/gists{/gist_id}", "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/nikomatsakis/starred{/own